properties.headline: Winter Storm Warning issued January 17 at 3:10PM CST until January 18 at 6:00AM CST by NWS Twin Cities/Chanhassen MN
properties.description:
...WINTER STORM WARNING TONIGHT FOLLOWED BY A BLIZZARD WARNING
SATURDAY FOR WESTERN INTO SOUTH CENTRAL MINNESOTA...

...WINTER STORM WARNING THROUGH SATURDAY FOR CENTRAL AND EASTERN
MINNESOTA INTO WEST CENTRAL WISCONSIN...

.Snow, heavy at times through the early evening, will begin to
taper off to light snow overnight. Blowing snow, with significant
reduction in surface visibility, will occur late tonight as winds
increase from the northwest. The worst conditions will occur in
west central, and into south central Minnesota. Surface visibility
will be near zero at times, especially in open country. In
addition, falling temperatures will lead to icy roads and very
cold temperatures, especially on Saturday.

This storm will impact travel. Expect snow-covered roads followed
by strong winds, blowing snow and falling temperatures.

* WHAT...For the Winter Storm Warning, Total snow accumulations
of 4 to 7 inches with ice accumulations of a light glaze.
Winds 25 to 30 mph with gusts as high as 40 mph. For the
Blizzard Warning on Saturday, widespread blowing snow and near
zero visibility will occur with the blizzard conditions. Winds
gusts will reach 45 to 50 mph.

* WHERE...Portions of south central, southwest and west central
Minnesota. Generally along and west of a line from Glenwood to
Willmar, to New Ulm, to Fairmont.

* WHEN...For the Winter Storm Warning, it continues through 6 AM
CST Saturday. For the Blizzard Warning, the warning begins 6
AM Saturday morning, and continues through 6 PM CST.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Areas of blowing
snow could significantly reduce visibility. The hazardous
conditions will impact the evening commute. Wind chills on
Saturday will drop as low as 30 below zero which could cause
frostbite on exposed skin in as little as 10 minutes.
properties.instruction:
If you must travel, keep an extra flashlight, food, and water in
your vehicle in case of an emergency.

Travel should be restricted to emergencies only. If you must
travel, have a winter survival kit with you. If you get stranded,
stay with your vehicle.

The latest road conditions for the state you are calling from can
be obtained by calling 5 1 1.

NWSheadline: WINTER STORM WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 AM CST SATURDAY... ...BLIZZARD WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 6 AM TO 6 PM CST SATURDAY
